enum MHD_HdrLineReadRes_ and enumerators: MHD_HDR_LINE_READING_GOT_HEADER, MHD_HDR_LINE_READING_NEED_MORE_DATA, MHD_HDR_LINE_READING_DATA_ERROR, MHD_HDR_LINE_READING_GOT_END_OF_HEADER
state constants: MHD_CONNECTION_FOOTERS_RECEIVING, MHD_CONNECTION_REQ_HEADERS_RECEIVING, MHD_CONNECTION_FULL_REQ_RECEIVED, MHD_CONNECTION_HEADERS_RECEIVED, MHD_CONNECTION_FOOTERS_RECEIVED
MHD_HEADER_KIND and MHD_FOOTER_KIND (constants passed to MHD_set_connection_value_n_nocheck_)

mhd_assert macro/definition (whether asserts have side-effects or are compiled out)
MHD_BUF_INC_SIZE and HTTP_VER_LEN (constants used in buffer/shift logic)
explanation: To determine whether any operations in get_req_headers constitute 'dead code' (i.e. can be removed without changing program behaviour) the analyzer must know every symbol that affects control flow or produces side-effects that other code relies on. The struct MHD_Connection and the listed fields are required because get_req_headers reads and writes many connection and request fields (state, rq counters, buffer pointers and sizes) — removing writes or reads could change observable behaviour. The enum values and state constants determine which branch is taken. get_req_header controls the primary loop (return codes and modifications to hdr_name/hdr_value and possibly to the connection), so its exact semantics and side-effects are essential. MHD_set_connection_value_n_nocheck_, MHD_connection_alloc_memory_, MHD_NO, MHD_HEADER_KIND and MHD_FOOTER_KIND are required because allocation/store success or failure changes execution (the failure branch performs error handling); whether that branch has observable effects depends on the implementation of these functions. The two handle_req_*_no_space functions are called in the failure branch and likely perform error responses or state changes — their side-effects determine whether that branch is behaviorally relevant. reset_rq_header_processing_state mutates connection processing state; knowing its effects is required to decide whether the 'reset' call is necessary. MHD_DLOG and HAVE_MESSAGES are required because logging calls are conditional; if logging is compiled out they might be dead — if logging has side-effects they are not. mhd_assert is required because many operations are only present as asserts — assertions may compile out; that changes whether those statements are dead. memmove and strlen are used in buffer manipulation and validation; memmove performs non-trivial memory writes (observable), and the constants MHD_BUF_INC_SIZE and HTTP_VER_LEN affect whether the shifting code runs. In short: to decide if a statement can be removed without affecting observable program behaviour you must know the return/side-effect semantics or compilation-time presence of each of the above symbols.
